the deteriorating economy is hitting consumers 
in northeastern states hardest according to loan delinquency data 
for the julyseptember quarter 
nationally the percentage of consumer loans 30 or more days 
delinquent was a seasonally adjusted 256 percent at the end of the 
third quarter virtually unchanged from the 255 percent rate at 
the end of the apriljune period the american bankers association 
said monday 
the rate was 246 percent at the end of the first quarter of 
1990 and 264 percent at the end of the fourth quarter of 1989 
however the lack of movement masked sharp variations among 
regions 
the top five delinquency rates were new hampshire 612 percent 
connecticut 553 percent puerto rico 518 percent 
massachusetts 485 percent and west virginia 434 percent 
rounding out the top 10 were new york rhode island maine alabama 
and new jersey 
delinquency rates were lowest in arizona 127 percent 
nebraska 133 percent south dakota 134 percent colorado 156 
percent and minnesota 162 percent the rest of the bottom 10 
were tennessee washington north carolina california and idaho 
robert h dugger chief economist of the bankers group said 
the survey combined with other data indicates consumers 
nationally continued to pay their bills in the third quarter but 
were scaling back borrowing as the economy headed into what many 
analysts say is a recession 
consumers are well aware of the slowing economy and are making 
efforts to consolidate and repay debts rather than take on new 
ones dugger said 
government data shows consumers are taking fewer loans he said 
while anecdotal evidence from bankers indicates that financially 
stronger households may be taking out less expensive and 
longerterm home equity loans in order to pay off other consumer 
loans and reduce their monthly payments 
dugger said he expected the number of consumers behind on loan 
payments to be higher when figures are reported for the final three 
months of this year 
federal reserve chairman alan greenspan has said the economy 
slipped into a meaningful downturn in october the result of 
higher oil prices and shaken consumer confidence stemming from 
iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait 
michael k evans a washington economic consultant said 
consumer loan delinquencies generally do not rise significantly 
until well into a recession 
consumers havent been too hard hit yet evans said i 
dont think gasoline prices have that big of an impact i dont 
want to say it doesnt hurt at all but people are taking it in 
stride theyre cutting into their savings on the grounds that its 
just temporary 
the delinquency rate includes seven different types of 
closedend consumer loans personal two types of auto loans 
mobile home recreational vehicle property improvement and second 
mortgages 
the rate for openended home equity lines of credit which are 
tracked separately edged up from 075 percent in the second 
quarter to 08 percent in the third 
the banking group surveyed 800 commercial banks tracking loans 
in all 50 states puerto rico and the district of columbia 
