<TEXT>
federal safety experts have warned for years 
that runway collisions like the one that killed eight people at 
detroit are a rising danger at increasingly congested us 
airports 
the national transportation safety board frustrated that many 
of its key accidentprevention recommendations have never been 
implemented voted in october to give the runway collision issue 
added urgency by placing it high on its list of most wanted 
safety improvements 
it is a serious problem said safety board spokesman mike 
benson after mondays runway collision of two northwest airlines 
passenger jets a dc9 and a 727 at detroit metropolitan airport 
weve said its serious benson said thats why weve 
made that safety area one of our most wanted recommendations 
according to government figures the nations airports reported 
382 runway incursions in 1987 incidents where an airplane taxied 
onto a runway without authorization from aircraft controllers or 
because of confusion in interpreting instructions the number of 
incidents declined to 190 in 1988 but they have been increasing 
since then 
aviations worst disaster was just such an ontheground 
accident two boeing 747s one operated by pan am and the other by 
the dutch airline klm collided on a foggy runway at tenerife in 
the canary islands on march 27 1977 
the collision of the jumbo jets killed 581 people 
in the detroit accident visibility at metropolitan airport was 
poor and the ground was wet from a morning snow and sleet storm 
that delayed flights 
tony dresden a spokesman for the national air traffic 
controllers association a union representing air controllers 
said preliminary reports from detroit controllers indicated that 
the dc9 pilot became lost on the runways 
the pilot gave the ground controller erroneous information 
about his position and turned right onto the runway where the 727 
was taxiing dresden said the dc9 pilot discovered at the 
very last moment where he was and so the ground controller told 
him to immediately get off that runway but it was too late 
the faa which oversees the nations air traffic control system 
had no immediate comment on dresdens statement 
a runway collision can have catastrophic effects since departing 
aircraft such as the two northwest jetliners at detroit are 
likely to be fully oaded with highly flammable jet fuel 
the safety board first addressed the runway incursion issue 
after three nearmisses by aircraft rolling down airport runways 
between june 1978 and february 1979 
in 1986 the safety board asked the faa to implement these 
measures 
require air traffic controllers to get confirmation from 
pilots in the form of reading back instructions they receive from 
the tower of all hold takeoff or crossing clearances and all 
clearances for access onto an active runway 
revise and enforce requirements to investigate and report 
operational or pilot errors that lead to runway incursions and to 
attempt to learn how and why they occur 
determine the most effective signs markings and procedures to 
prevent pilot induced runway incursions 
the faa said in april it was considering the readback 
requirement 
the safety board investigates all major transportation accidents 
involving us carriers setting a probable cause for each a team 
of investigators was dispatched hours after the detroit accident 
the board investigates about 2500 accidents a year and has 
issued nearly 8200 safety recommendations since its creation in 
1967 since it has no enforcement powers it can only recommend that 
safety improvements be made 
the boards most wanted list of such proposed improvements 
include recommendations involving cruise ships fishing boats 
automobile accidents truck safety and pipelines as well as several 
in the field of aviation 
