<TEXT>
iraq claims more than 1400 children under 
5 years old have died due to shortages caused by the un embargo 
but doctors and western diplomats say there are no serious 
shortages of food or basic medicines 
iraq said today it was reducing the december rations of sugar 
and tea for adults by onefourth but it said the allotment for all 
other foods covered by rationing would remain the same 
the report of child deaths stemming from the economic sanctions 
came from iraqi health minister abdulsalam mohammed saeed 
he told the official iraqi news agency on monday that 1416 
children had died and that many of them had not received needed 
medicine or sufficient milk because of shortages created by the 
embargo 
there is no way to independently verify iraqi figures on child 
deaths or to confirm how many if any of the children died for those 
reasons 
the government is the sole importer of medicine in iraq and the 
only official source of information on supply however a doctor at 
one baghdad hospital who spoke on condition of anonymity said 
recently there was no shortage of basic medicines or medical 
supplies in iraq 
iraqis say they can buy medicines and powdered milk for their 
children but mostly only at exorbitant black market rates 
western diplomats in baghdad who generally discount reports of 
acute food and medicine shortages said iraq received more than 30 
tons of medical supplies between midoctober and midnovember alone 
in exchange for the release of western hostages 
another 40 tons of medical supplies reportedly were shipped to 
iraq in late november diplomats said italy alone sent 25 tons of 
medicine mainly measles polio and diphtheria vaccines on nov 
24 all of it was earmarked for iraqi children 
some diplomats and medical personnel in baghdad suggested last 
month that iraq might be stockpiling medicine in case of war and 
that some of the reported shortages resulted from profiteering 
governmentrun hospitals report shortages of antibiotics 
medicines vaccines and baby formula and tell patients they must 
bring their own 
iraqis say prices at pharmacies and on the black market are 
often at least five times higher than normal they say many 
pharmacies enticed by higher profits have diverted stocks to the 
black market 
the government rationing plan instituted in september limits 
each child under a year old to three 16ounce cans of baby formula 
a month at governmentsubsidized stores each can costs 225 at 
the official rate 
iraqis forced to supplement their childrens diet with powdered 
milk bought on the black market pay as much as 40 dinars for a 
22pound can that price beyond the means of many iraqis amounts 
to 120 at the official rate and between 8 and 13 at varying 
blackmarket rates 
iraq has often claimed the sanctions are inhumane and deny food 
milk and medicine to children but the diplomats note that the 
sanctions do not prohibit imports of food and medicine for 
humanitarian reasons 
food shelves at private stores and vegetable markets in the 
capital are well stocked often with goods looted from kuwait or 
smuggled in from iran or jordan 
prices of many goods have soared to three and four times their 
normal cost but with the arrival of looted supplies from kuwait 
the price of some goods such as cooking oil and rice has actually 
dropped 
