weekend 
neither gorbachev nor bakatin immediately commented on the 
report in komsomolskaya pravda which added to a swirl of 
speculation in the supreme soviet legislature on the intentions 
behind gorbachevs latest shakeup 
traditionalist hardline legislators praised gorbachevs 
decision to dismiss bakatin as interior minister and replace him 
with a kgb general who is expected to crack down on independence 
movements and black marketeering 
but the newspaper report raised the possibility that gorbachev 
could be feinting left and striking right removing a favorite of 
reformists only to place him in a more important post 
the interior ministry commands the soviet militia or police 
which includes special riot squads and paramilitary troops 
bakatin is popular among reformers who support the independence 
movements in the baltics and other restive republics because he 
put a tight rein on the riot police after 19 peaceful demonstrators 
