<TEXT>
the federal reserve in a move designed to 
ease the socalled credit crunch announced today it is 
eliminating bank reserve requirements on some deposits 
the board took action at this time in response to mounting 
evidence that commercial banks have been tightening their standards 
of creditworthiness and the terms and conditions for many types of 
loans the announcement said 
while much of this tightening has been welcome from a safety 
and soundness standpoint it has in recent months begun to exert a 
contractionary influence on the economy it added 
there currently is a 3 percent reserve requirement on 
nonpersonal time deposits maturing in less than 18 months which 
are mostly corporate cds and net eurocurrency liabilities the 
requirement means banks have to hold in reserve sums equal to 3 
percent of the amount 
both requirements will be lowered to zero in coming weeks 
the fed said lower reserve requirements reduce bank costs and 
provide incentives to lend to creditworthy borrowers thus 
countering to some extent the recent tightening in credit 
terms 
both federal reserve chairman alan greenspan and treasury 
secretary nicholas f brady have said tight credit is causing 
problems for many businesses 
some critics contend government officials are being overzealous 
in interpreting banking regulations in the wake of the savings and 
bond debacle brady has urged regulators not to be 
unrealistically negative in evaluating loans and urged bankers 
to keep lending to your good customers 
