house speaker thomas s foley today dashed any 
hopes for a proposed change in house rules that would have 
bolstered the democratic majority in 1992 
the house democratic caucus had been scheduled to vote on a 
proposed rule change that would let lawmakers accept unlimited 
donations to cover legal costs they may incur in the upcoming 
redistricting 
but foley dwash emerged from the meeting to tell reporters 
it will not happen were going to review the situation 
boundaries of congressional districts will be changed nationwide 
as a result of the 1990 census because the changes could 
critically affect many 1992 house races key redistricting plans 
could wind up being settled in the courts 
rep martin frost dtexas who heads a democratic group that is 
reviewing house rules and making suggestions for changes said 
before todays vote the likelihood is high that a number of 
members would want legal advice 
foley in quashing the idea provided no other details on the 
issue which when first disclosed on monday attracted criticism 
fred wertheimer president of common cause said his citizens 
group was urging house democrats to reject the proposal which he 
said runs counter to public demand for tighter ethics rules 
its as if no one there is paying any attention to the keating 
five hearings going on across the street in the other chamber 
said wertheimer referring to the senate ethics hearings on 
allegations of influencepeddling in the savings and loan scandal 
the proposed rule change would create an outrageous loophole 
at a time when the house should be taking steps to eliminate the 
ability of outside interest groups to provide money to elected 
officials who decide their interests wertheimer said 
normally house rules limit gifts to members to 200 under 
frosts proposal that rule would be waived for any donations for 
legal costs associated with redistricting in addition federal 
election law limits on campaign donations would not apply 
lawmakers would have to report contributions and spending from 
their special redistricting accounts the reporting would be done 
as part of congress annual financial disclosure process which 
allows a lag of up to 1 years before a transaction must be 
reported 
another leadership proposal to help incumbents would change the 
rules in the taxpayerfinanced house recording studio which 
lawmakers use to make prerecorded messages to their home 
districts 
lawmakers now must pay studio costs from their office accounts 
the new proposal would let them accept private reimbursement for 
those expenses thus freeing more office account money for mass 
mailings and other purposes 
decisions on the rules changes were coming a day after the 
democrats and republicans reelected their leadership teams from 
the last congress 
house majority leader richard gephardt dmo told the 
democrats they faced the challenge of improving the reputation 
and credibility of this institution 
gephardt and foley were chosen without opposition by the 
democrats to continue in their posts as were majority whip william 
h gray dpa and caucus chairman steny hoyer dmd 
on the republican side minority leader robert michel of 
illinois and minority whip newt gingrich of georgia had no 
opponents 
but while the democrats were pursuing advantage over the gop 
the republicans were fighting among themselves monday 
the no 3ranked republican conference chairman jerry lewis of 
california had to survive a vigorous challenge by rep carl 
pursell of michigan and rep guy vander jagt of michigan held on 
to his chairmanship of the republican congressional campaign 
committee in a tough battle with rep don sundquist of tennessee 
