<TEXT>
iran has executed more than 5000 people in the 
past three years many for political beliefs and the government 
has done little to stem human rights abuses amnesty international 
said today 
despite some changes since the 1989 death of ayatollah ruhollah 
khomeini government critics continued to be arrested and tortured 
some for no more than signing a letter criticizing lack of human 
rights and freedoms the international human rights group said in a 
report 
amnesty quoted exprisoners as saying a death commission of 
iranian officials chose prisoners every day and sent them to their 
deaths after a cursory interrogation if their views were not 
acceptable 
in 1988 more than 2500 political prisoners were killed 
secretly in a few months on orders of the commission the 
londonbased organization said 
thousands more have been executed after summary trials in which 
they were convicted of criminal offenses amnesty said crackdowns 
on drug trafficking led to more than 1100 executions in 1989 it 
said 
most criminal executions are by hanging but some people are 
beheaded forced to jump from high places or stoned to death while 
buried to the waist amnesty said 
a photo in the report shows the bodies of nine men hanging from 
a crane on the back of a truck 
the report says that after executions these portable gibbets may 
be driven through the streets with the bodies still hanging from 
them 
the united nations is considering a draft resolution condemning 
rights violations in iran based on findings of its salvadoran 
envoy reynaldo galindo pohl he noted abuses of due process and a 
startling number of executions 
iran on monday persuaded the un general assembly to delete all 
references in the resolution to executions illtreatment and 
torture in return it pledged to continue cooperating with un 
human rights investigations and to begin letting the red cross 
visit its prisons 
a vote on the original draft resolution would have been a 
humiliating public rebuke for iran which undoubtedly would have 
refused to allow future visits by human rights experts 
tehran radio on monday accused the united nations of using the 
original draft resolution to try to pressure iran into dropping its 
opposition to usled forces arrayed against iraq in the persian 
gulf region 
the actions of amnesty international and the human rights 
commission of the united nations tell of a vast calculated 
political pressure whose roots should be searched outside the 
framework of human rights the radio said 
amnesty said the iranian government has consistently refused to 
answer the groups questions and ignored its requests to send a 
delegation 
despite changes brought by the 1988 end of irans war with iraq 
and the death of khomeini the government has done little to 
improve human rights protection the report says 
amnesty which opposes the death penalty said people are often 
executed days after their arrest with no legal counsel no right to 
call witnesses and no right to appeal 
torture beating and intimidation of prisoners is reportedly 
widespread the organization said 
more than 20 prominent government critics including several 
exministers were arrested in june after they supported an open 
letter to president hashemi rafsanjani criticizing lack of freedoms 
and human rights amnesty said 
the group expressed fears the imprisoned critics were being 
tortured to extract confessions of involvement in socalled 
counterrevolutionary activity 
executions for criminal offenses are usually announced in the 
iranian press but political executions are usually carried out in 
secret the report says for this reason the numbers of political 
executions which have taken place in iran are disputed 
but amnesty has recorded the names of over 2000 prisoners 
reportedly executed in secret from july 1988 to january 1989 
there is overwhelming evidence that in the latter part of 1988 
the iranian government carried out the largest wave of political 
executions in iran since the early 1980s it said 
after the iranian revolution of 1979 which ousted shah reza 
pahlavi and brought khomeini to power thousands of political 
opponents were executed 
amnesty said former prisoners suggested the 198889 executions 
might have resulted from two factors 
the ceasefire in the war with iraq which distracted 
international attention from the prisoners 
government reprisal for an armed incursion by an iraqbased 
mujahedeen khalq or peoples holy warriors opposition group 
</TEXT>
