president hussain muhammad ershad bowed 
to an increasingly violent campaign for his ouster and agreed today 
to quit as soon as the opposition nominates a replacement state 
radio said 
parliament will meet saturday to try to choose a successor the 
radio said in a latenight news bulletin 
ershad had offered monday to step down shortly before elections 
scheduled for june but the opposition which had staged a 
sevenweek campaign to drive him from office rebuffed that offer 
and demanded that he step down now 
the 60yearold former army general took over bangladesh one of 
the worlds poorest countries in a bloodless coup in 1982 
ershad had declared a state of emergency nov 27 to quash the 
opposition campaign seeking his ouster 
immediately after the announcement hundreds of opposition 
workers thronged the streets of the capital chanting slogans and 
setting off firecrackers 
where is ershad now they shouted 
pressure on ershad had been building steadily at least 19 of 
his supporters resigned from parliament the opposition called for 
daily dawntodusk strikes and scores of civil servants quit their 
jobs 
as part of the antiershad program the countrys two largest 
cities were paralyzed today by a general strike 
word of the presidents latest offer came after the opposition 
announced new protests to intensify its campaign to oust him 
in the capital dhaka few buses or rickshaws were on the 
streets today and shops were closed banks and most businesses were 
closed government offices opened but few arrived for work 
in a nationally televised speech monday night ershad offered to 
resign 45 days before presidential elections set for june handing 
over power to a nominee of the opposition 
ershad had said in addition to stepping down before june 
elections he was willing to dissolve parliament and hold 
parliamentary elections simultaneously with the presidential vote 
with international observers as witnesses 
but opposition leaders made no move to rescind their call for 
daily eighthour strikes 
his offer is vague and we dont accept his proposal to hold 
presidential and parliamentary elections sheik hasina leader of 
the awami league the second major opposition group had sad after 
the first announcement 
groups of 100 to 200 demonstrators marched through dhakas 
central mouchak commercial district earlier today shouting the 
last days of ershad have arrived and give ershad one more push 
and he will fall 
on monday the government lifted press censorship but 
journalists decided to continue their strike until the state of 
emergency is lifted 
ershad also said on monday he would lift the emergency on dec 
16 the 19th anniversary of bangladeshs independence from 
pakistan 
his coup in 1982 followed a chaotic succession of presidents 
installed by the military after the former province of pakistan won 
its independence in the 1971 civil war bangladesh with 110 
million people is among the poorest and most densely populated 
countries in the world 
