<TEXT>
moscow president mikhail s gorbachev told the soviet 
legislature today that he will crack down on black marketeering and 
boost food imports to feed the population during this 
shortageplagued winter 
he promised that his actions would guarantee the food supply to 
the nation for the next three or four months 
gorbachev also said his upcoming shakeup of the soviet cabinet 
would drastically shrink it aides said its membership would drop 
from 56 ministers to little more than a dozen 
the president presented draft constitutional amendments for 
revamping of the soviet government and won immediate approval of 
them by a vote of 28117 
the larger congress of peoples deputies which convenes dec 
17 also must ratify the amendments 
describing the rampant black market in food in the soviet union 
gorbachev said a survey of 50 state stores found that when they 
close they have a third shift when employees sell the food 
illegally 
salesclerks in soviet stores often set aside choice goods to 
sell at inflated prices so they can pocket the profits 
within the next two or three weeks we think we can control 
the situation he said referring to the black market 
gorbachev also said he had obtained loans and credits to import 
flour sugar vegetable oil margarine meat milk products and 
eggs 
during the first three months of 1991 he said the soviet 
government would spend the equivalent of 21 billion rubles on 
food including 
10 miliion tons of grain 19 million tons of sugar 156000 
tons of flour 277000 tons of sunflower oil 357000 tons of meat 
and meat products 45 million tons of milk products and 110000 
tons of groats 
the government also is stepping up its construction program for 
food processing and will set aside 12 million acres for 
individual farming to boost domestic production he said 
gorbachev did not specify what types of food processing 
industries would be built or whether the additional land for 
individual farming would actually be owned by private farmers or 
collective farms 
on monday the parliament of the russian federation approved a 
measure allowing private land ownership but the national 
legislature has not taken that step so far 
the united states germany and italy have begun sending food aid 
to the soviet union and other western and asian countries have 
pledged their support soviet officials blame problems with food 
distribution for increasingly empty grocery store shelves 
gorbachevs overhaul of his administrative structure would 
shrink the council of ministers and rename it the cabinet of 
ministers 
presidential spokesman vitaly ignatienko later said the new 
cabinet would have 12 to 15 members asked when the appointments 
would be made to the new body he said soon in our lifetime 
the cabinet of ministers would be responsible to the president 
and control the national budget energy industries transportation 
environmental protection as well as credit and foreign currency 
in conjunction with the republics it would work out a national 
program for health insurance maternity and child care issues 
culture and education and basic scientific research 
the cabinet would continue to include the prime ministers of the 
15 republics in addition to the federal officials the interfax 
news agency reported 
the federation council an advisory board representing the 15 
republics would be enhanced and take responsibility for carrying 
out the decisions that it approves 
this could ease gorbachevs authority problems by enlisting the 
republic presidents aid in carrying out kremlin decisions 
recently many republics have rejected orders from the central 
government 
the reform also calls for creating a vice presidency and a 
national security council it would abolish his presidential 
council itself only a few months old 
the national security council would maintain national defense 
maintenance of a reliable state economic and ecological 
security and handle natural disasters and emergencies interfax 
reported 
the 15 soviet republics would not have national security 
responsibilities 
the constitutional changes would preserve the post of prime 
minister to be nominated by the president and approved by the 
supreme soviet legislature 
many lawmakers said they were disappointment with gorbachevs 
speech 
a lot of questions remain said fyodor burlatsky the 
president explained some general ideas but we dont know the real 
functions for the new institutions burlatsky said 
