bombing nor the drug enforcement administration found evidence to 
substantiate broadcast reports that terrorists took advantage of an 
undercover dea operation to smuggle explosives aboard the plane 
nbc and abc both reported in late october that security at the 
frankfurt airport where the new yorkbound flight originated had 
been relaxed to accommodate dea investigators who were tracking 
usbound drug shipments 
but deputy attorney general william p barr said in a statement 
tuesday that no evidence has been revealed to support any of the 
allegations that a dea operation was in any way involved in the pan 
am tragedy 
dea had no investigative or operational activity in effect on 
dec 21 1988 that involved the use of pan am flight 103 or 
frankfurt international airport barr said 
a bomb destroyed the plane as it flew over lockerbie scotland 
killing 259 people on board and 11 on the ground the flight 
originated in frankfurt with a stop in london where passengers and 
luggage were transferred to another aircraft 
law enforcement officials in britain and germany continue to 
investigate the bombing along with the fbi 
investigators believe the bombing was carried out by members of 
the popular front for the liberation of palestine but the fbi has 
not yet produced enough evidence to bring criminal charges against 
specific individuals according to law enforcement sources 
barr also said the dea inquiry found that its agents did not 
circumvent security measures at the frankfurt airport at any 
time 
barrs statement also discounted reports that one of the 
passengers killed in the bombing khalid nazir jaafar had been a 
dea informant and was cooperating in an undercover operation to 
trace drug shipments from the middle east to detroit 
jaafar was not an informant nor was he working for the dea in 
any other capacity on dec 21 1988 or at any other time barr 
said the dea had found allegations that khalid jaafar visited a 
dea office are incorrect 
the statement was issued as attorney general dick thornburgh was 
in the midst of a weeklong european trip on wednesday thornburgh 
is scheduled to attend the rome conference of trevi an 
organization of european law enforcement officials 
dea quickly denied the network reports after they were 
broadcast and the justice department said there was no evidence 
at that point to substantiate them but the justice department 
ordered a further inquiry into the matter 
