<TEXT>
most us hospitals surveyed have admitted at 
least one aids patient but their policies on testing for aids vary 
widely often pitting the interests of patients against those of 
doctors and nurses researchers say 
to a certain extent hospitals are in a nowin situation 
since policy provisions protecting patients may be incompatible 
with provisions protecting healthcare personnel said the 
researchers who surveyed 561 hospitals 
not only do hospitals face potential risk of litigation from 
patients for violation of their rights but hospitals also may be 
held responsible for placing healt care personnel at increased 
risk by withholding relevant information about infected patients 
the researchers said 
they drew their sample randomly from a list of all nonfederal 
general acutecare hospitals with more than 25 beds and reported 
their findings in wednesdays journal of the american medical 
association 
about twothirds of the hospitals had at least one aids patient 
including 40 percent of rural hospitals indicating aids is no 
longer a disease of big cities said dr charles e lewis 
professor of medicine at the university of california los angeles 
he and kathleen montgomery of the university of california 
riverside found that 83 percent of hospitals have formal written 
policies about testing patients for infection with hiv the aids 
virus 
most policies have provisions protecting patients rights the 
researchers found for example 78 percent required the patients 
informed consent before the test whether written or verbal 66 
percent required a written consent and 75 percent required that 
patients who tested positive be told the results 
many policies also had provisions protecting healthcare 
workers the researchers said for example 56 percent required 
that test results appear in patients records 38 percent required 
a review of treatment plans when a patient tests positive and 3 
percent required that hivpositive patients be discharged or 
transferred 
carisa cunningham a new york spokeswoman for an aids activist 
group said patient care should be first priority in any hospitals 
policy 
the question we always ask is what is the information needed 
for who needs it and why said cunningham of the gay mens 
health crisis 
if health care providers want the information so they can 
transfer a patient to another hospital and not have to deal with 
them thats not acceptable 
dr frank rhame director of the hiv clinic at the university of 
minnesota hospital in minneapolis said the study is the largest to 
explore policies about hiv testing at us hospitals 
but he cautioned that policies and actual practices often 
differ 
what most people have recommended and whats actually being 
done and what the policy may be are at considerable variance he 
said in a telephone interview 
i think that its important to evaluate the actual practice 
he said its harder youve actually got to go in the hospital 
and get a record of every hiv test thats been performed and verify 
that the patient was notified 
