<TEXT>
why did dinosaurs disappear scientists 
wrote 2000 studies blaming asteroids volcanoes slow climate 
change or even constipation researchers said tuesday they think 
they found the smoking gun a 110milewide impact crater in 
mexico 
but dont bet the 12yearlong debate is over 
earlier evidence suggests other asteroids or comets struck earth 
near manson iowa and in the caribbean off colombia or cuba when 
the dinosaurs went extinct 65 million years ago 
some scientists say certain basalt rock deposits around the 
world suggest another object also smacked into the planet to help 
trigger mass extinction 
we think we have found the smoking gun but there may be other 
guns and maybe a firing squad said bill boynton of the 
university of arizona at tucson 
the latest theory came during the american geophysical unions 
fall meeting the convention of 4400 earth scientists leans 
heavily toward the theory that killer asteroids sent dinosaurs to 
oblivion 
the idea is that an incoming 6milewide asteroid or comet or 
a shower of them smacked into the earth with the force of 70 
million onemegaton bombs kicking debris into the atmosphere and 
causing radical environmental damage that wiped out the dinosaurs 
and up to 75 percent of all living species 
some researchers think the impacts blocked out sunlight wiping 
out food supplies others theorized somewhat in jest that changes 
in vegetation upset the dinosaurs diet leaving them fatally 
constipated 
other possible deadly effects of asteroids hitting earth include 
acid rain giant tidal waves dark freezing weather global warming 
by the greenhouse effect and worldwide forest fires said geologist 
walter alvarez of the university of california at berkeley who 
helped start the debate in 1978 
jay melosh of the university of arizona said worldwide soot 
deposits support the fire theory he believes a single asteroid 
plowed into the earth and sent molten rock droplets skyward where 
they heated the atmosphere and caused 700degree surface 
temperatures 
its enough heat to ignite vegetation melosh said 
unprotected animals would have been broiled in their tracks 
alvarez his father the late nobel laureate physicist luis w 
alvarez and others found deposits of 65millionyearold iridium 
metal in rocks around the world iridium is rare on earth but less 
rare in asteroids and comets the killerasteroid theory was born 
because an impact would have spread iridium dust around the globe 
some researchers still argue the dinosaurs were rendered extinct 
by gradual natural climate changes or by climate disruption from 
huge volcanic eruptions they demanded asteroid advocates show 
where the object or objects hit earth 
the 22milewide crater in iowa was created by an impact that 
probably wasnt large enough to cause mass extinction alvarez 
said 
last may alan hildebrand boynton and others in arizona 
proposed one culprit impact crater in the caribbean off colombias 
coast as evidence they cited rock deposits in haiti and the us 
gulf coast caused by asteroidinduced rock fallout and 3milehigh 
tidal waves 
in their latest study presented by boynton they propose 
another asteroid struck shallow mexican waters the impact site is 
a 110milewide crater now covered by sediment on the coast of 
mexicos yucatan peninsula near the town of chicxulub the crater 
contains oncemelted rock and shocked quartz grains that indicate 
something jolted the shallow sea floor 
boynton called the site ground zero but said another 
asteroid probably hit offshore from columbia others say there was 
in impact near cuba 
brown universitys peter schultz said laboratory studies show a 
single 6milewide asteroid hitting earth at a 15degree angle 
could have broken into 1000 smaller pieces that caused a series of 
impact craters 
alvarez said there also must be other impacts because some 
debris found in worldwide rock deposits contains tiny balls of 
basalt glass that couldnt have come from an asteroid smacking into 
iowa or the yucatan 
alvarez said the debate is so important it has generated 2000 
studies since 1978 
we wouldnt be here if it hadnt been for the extinction of 
the dinosaurs alvarez said they were ruling the place 
mammals were just running around underfoot until the impact killed 
the dinosaurs and let us evolve 
but if a huge asteroid impact happened today it would cause the 
extinction of the human race said ronald prinn of the 
massachusetts institute of technology 
</TEXT>
