i never was a member of the communist party unlike many who 
now accuse me beron said alluding to former marxists who went 
over to the opposition in the last year after bulgarias communist 
dictatorship crumbled 
beron spoke from budapest hungary en route to bulgaria he 
insisted that his police activities served the state and not the 
communist party 
hours after union leader konstantin trenchev leveled his 
accusations parliament voted overwhelmingly to ask the interior 
ministry to hand over files to a special legislative committee 
within a week on all legislators who had worked with the secret 
police 
socialist premier andrei lukanov and his government of former 
communists were toppled last friday by a udf boycott of the 
legislature prolonged street demonstrations and a general strike 
called by the podkrepa trade union federation lukanovs 
administration came under fire largely because of its links with 
the former communist system the communists changed their name to 
the bulgarian socialist party after the old regime fell 
the former communists won june elections but saw their 
popularity fade as economic troubles mounted bulgaria now rations 
basic foods and energy 
the socialists are negotiating the makeup of a new government 
with the udf 
trenchev chairman of podkrepa said in an interview our 
union has a list with 71 names of deputies who were employees of 
the former secret police these people must leave parliament 
he said 54 of the deputies were socialists and 17 were members 
of the udf including beron 
the allegations were likely to split the opposition at a time 
when it needs unity in its bid for a major share of power in a new 
government and to further polarize parliament that could make it 
harder to approve economic reforms needed to bring bulgaria out of 
its worst postworld war ii economic crisis 
in separate comments the state bta news agency quoted trenchev 
as saying beron has been an informer of the thought police 
of the totalitarian regime 
prominent members of the udf refused to dismiss allegations of 
further police informers in their ranks 
i cannot exclude the possibility that a whole bunch of our 
people were employees of the security police in the past and 
continue in such functions even today alexander yordanov said in 
an interview 
in such a case the communist party remains in power in 
bulgaria and the system remains totalitarian he said 
unlike other east bloc countries where communists were ousted 
by popular pressure reformist communists toppled bulgarias 
longtime communist strongman todor zhivkov in november 1989 
the former communists now socialists are widely considered 
the heirs of a bankrupt communist system that was based on police 
state controls a centralized economy and dependence on moscow 
