<TEXT>
the ability of mammograms to detect breast 
cancer early has improved significantly since 1985 though slightly 
higher radiation is being used the food and drug administration 
said tuesday 
the greater radiation is justified by the improved quality of 
images the agency said the radiation is still within fda safety 
guidelines and is about twothirds lower than 1979 levels 
fda surveys of mammography equipment in 1985 showed that 36 
produced substandard images a survey by the agency in 1988 found 
the rate had declined to 13 percent 
i hope the surveys will encourage women to make greater use of 
mammography said dr james mason assistant secretary for health 
at the department of health and human services early detection 
and treatment offer women their best chance of surviving breast 
cancer 
the national cancer institute recommends that women over 40 have 
regular mammograms 
a report on the fdas surveys was published in the november 
issue of the journal radiology the agency said 
to test the xray machines used for mammography the fda uses a 
plastic device embedded with tiny objects this device is xrayed 
and the quality of the image is based on the number of the tiny 
objects that cn be seen 
the acceptable score for an image is 8 the fda said in 1985 
the average score was 78 and in 1988 the average had climbed to 
99 
the better quality in todays imaging devices is partly because 
of improvements in equipment including more use of xray machines 
that are specifically designed for mammography according to fred 
rueter of the fdas center for devices and radiological health one 
of the authors of the article 
he also said screen and film systems more sensitive to xrays 
are helping to produce clearer pictures 
fda officials said that even a substandard image may still 
detect cancer earlier than if a woman relies only on breast 
selfexamination alone 
but some members of congress are concerned that only one out of 
five mammography facilities meets the voluntary professional 
standards of the american college of radiology 
several members plan to introduce legislation next year that 
would set minimum federal safety standards for mammography 
services 
