a pipe carrying electrical wires broke loose 
from the roof of the nations fourthlongest land tunnels tuesday 
striking two buses and a car during evening rush hour police said 
one woman was injured 
more than 500 cars were stuck in the liberty tunnels through 
mount washington for about 45 minutes after five sections of tubing 
fell out of their brackets onto the outbound lanes at about 5 pm 
said pittsburgh police batallion chief john schemm 
the tubing contained lowvoltage electrical wire and 
communications wires police said 
police closed both inbound and outbound lanes snarling traffic 
that was leaving downtown pittsburgh for the heavily populated 
southern suburbs ramps leading to the tunnels also were closed 
police chief mayer deroy said one woman was injured apparently 
not seriously when the pipe hit the roof of her car and dented it 
the nature of her injury was not immediately disclosed 
passengers on two port authority transit buses were escorted 
from the tunnel on foot police and firefighters backed some of the 
cars out of the tunnel and were able to slowly move one lane of 
traffic past the fallen pipe 
the liberty bridge which feeds the tunnels was closed 
temporarily but reopened shortly after the accident tunnel 
traffic was redirected over local roads on mount washington 
police and the state transportation department which owns the 
tunnels were considering keeping the outbound lanes closed until 
wednesday evening for repairs deroy said 
the only tunnels in america longer than the liberty tunnels are 
tw interstate 70 tunnels in colorado and the allegheny tunnels on 
the pennsylvania turnpike 
