president hussain muhammad ershad 
capitulated to a 7weekold campaign for his ouster tuesday 
promising to resign as soon as the opposition chooses a 
replacement 
staterun radio announced the move in a latenight news 
bulletin soon afterward hundreds of people thronged the streets 
defying a curfew that restricted civilians to their homes 
many danced set off fire crackers in celebration and shouted 
slogans 
where is ershad now some chanted seize the airport so he 
cannot flee catch ershad kill his ministers 
at least 1000 people attacked a downtown office of ershads 
jatiya party reporters at the scene said portraits of ershad and 
office furniture were thrown into the street and set on fire they 
said 
security forces did not intervene or attempt to get people to 
return to their homes but troops were seen being deployed outside 
the homes of government ministers to prevent further attacks 
the radio bulletin said a special session of parliament was 
scheduled for sunday to ratify the choice of ershads replacement 
sheik hasina one of two opposition leaders heading the 
antiershad campaign called his resignation a peoples 
victory 
we are watching everything until the final game is over she 
said adding that choosing a replacement for ershad was not a 
problem 
the campaign for ershads ouster had mushroomed in recent weeks 
doctors university professors some of ershads parliamentarians 
and civil servants have resigned in solidarity with the opposition 
last week ershad imposed a state of emergency and suspended all 
civil rights in an attempt to crush the movement 
the army had been called out to prevent street protests against 
his rule and the opposition claimed that at least 100 political 
activists had been shot and killed the government said only six 
people had died 
despite the crackdown the protests continued on monday ershad 
offered to resign 45 days before junes presidential vote he also 
offered to dissolve the legislature and hold simultaneous elections 
for the presidency and parliament 
the opposition said his concessions were not sufficient and 
urged daily dawntodusk strikes to force the presidents immediate 
resignation 
ms hasina and the second opposition leader khaleda zia have 
opposed ershad since the former army general took power in a 1982 
coup but political differences between the two hindered earlier 
efforts to depose him 
the latest campaign was launched in october after the two said 
they had resolved their differences 
ms hasina is the daughter of sheik mujibur rahman bangladeshs 
first president mrs zia is the widow of ziaur rehman another 
former president both men were assassinated 
on monday the president said in a nationally televised speech 
that the emergency restrictions would be lifted on dec 16 the 
19th anniversary of bangladeshs independence from pakistan he 
also announced the immediate lifting of press censorship which had 
been imposed along with the emergency 
but on tuesday at least 19 lawmakers from ershads jatiya party 
resigned from parliament according to a letter circulated by 
speaker shamsul huda chowdhury 
the party holds 266 of 300 seats giasuddin ahmed one lawmaker 
who resigned later said the parliament has now become isolated 
from the people 
despite a ban on political meetings leaders of the three major 
opposition alliances addressed rallies in dhaka and announced daily 
protest strikes 
cars stayed off the streets and shops were closed in the 
capital and in the southern port city of chittagong 
banks and most businesses were shut government offices opened 
in dhaka but with most transportation off the roads few employees 
showed up for work 
if ershads replacement is chosen by the opposition and approved 
by parliament it will be the first peaceful transition of power in 
bangladesh the country has had nine presidents since it gained 
independence in 1971 and all have taken over after assassinations 
or military coups ershad has ruled about half that time 
bangladesh one of the poorest nations in the world has more 
than 107 million people it is bordered by india burma and the bay 
of bengal 
