<TEXT>
a halfcentury after a collection of 
spanish civil war photographs belonging to the late robert capa 
disappeared the foreign ministry on tuesday made public a 
catalogue of the original prints 
capas brother cornell capa who was instrumental in 
identifying the 97 prints looked on 
cornell capa now 72 and chief of the new yorkbased 
international center of photography catalogued the prints as works 
of his older brother or of david seymour cofounder with robert 
capa of the magnum photo agency or of capas companion gerda 
taro 
the younger capa himself a photographer who did the lab work 
for much of robert capas spanish photos said the 54yearold 
prints were in excellent condition 
he said the negatives had disappeared somewhere along the 
line probably in the next war world war ii 
robert capa born endre erno friedmann in pest hungary in 
1913 began his storied career as a war photographer in the 193639 
spanish conflict 
he covered the allied landings in north africa and normandy the 
liberation of paris the war in china and the birth of israel he 
died in 1954 after stepping on an antipersonnel mine in indochina 
capa changed his name in 1936 and became a us citizen in 
1946 
his photographs of spanish loyalist soldiers and militiamen 
fighting rebellious troops led by gen francisco franco and of 
refugees fleeing aerial bombardments brought the fratricidal 
conflict into the consciousness of a world edging slowing toward 
world war ii 
included in the collection is a highquality print of capas 
falling soldier taken at the cordoba front in early september 
1936 
the stark photo of the loyalist soldier falling backward after 
being shot his rifle in his right hand became perhaps the 
bestknown image of the spanish war 
until the late 1970s most spaniards were not familiar with 
capas photos of their war the pictures were published abroad and 
because they highlighted the republican side copies or collections 
of the photos were not readily available in postwar spain 
the prints showed up at the foreign ministry in madrid in march 
1979 in a small suitcase accompanied by a letter from swedish 
ambassador lennart petri 
petri explained that the unidentified collection was delivered 
to the swedish legation in vichy france during the war under 
mysterious circumstances and was later shipped to the foreign 
ministry in stockholm for safekeeping until spain returned to 
democracy 
franco ruled spain from 1939 until he died in 1975 spain 
returned to full democracy four years later 
archivists determined that capa gave the collection to juan 
negrin then prime minister who went into exile in france in 1939 
and died there in 1956 
it wasnt until 1987 however that serious efforts were made to 
identify the photographs at least five of which had never been 
published 
foreign ministry archivist mercedes perez vera said the photos 
would become the property of the spanish state 
the question remains whether the collection will join the civil 
war archives in salamanca available only to researchers or 
become part of a museum collection open to the public 
cornell capa obtained a set of copy negatives and prints for his 
brothers estate 
the edition of the catalogue was limited to 1000 copies 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

