the immigration and naturalization service 
said tuesday it had released 75 salvadorans from custody in 
anticipation of a new form of legal residence for them 
the 75 were those who may qualify for socalled temporary 
protected status under the new immigration law signed last week 
by president bush 
this provision was established for salvadorans illegally in this 
country who fear returning to their wartorn homeland but 
nonetheless do not qualify for regular refgee status 
to be admitted to legal residence as a refugee an immigrant 
must demonstrate a wellfounded fear of persecution at home 
the immigration and naturalization service in the past has 
contended that most salvadorans who enter the united states 
illegally could not qualify as refugees 
the new law permits those salvadorans in the united states 
before sept 19 and here continuously since then to apply for 
temporary protected status as of jan 2 permitting them to 
work legally and banning their deportation 
the law contains provision for eventual extension to citizens of 
other nations temporary protected status is to last only 18 
months from jan 1 
an ins statement quoted the head of the service gene mcnary as 
saying in keeping with the humanitarian spirit of the temporary 
protected status program the service was releasing salvadorans 
in custody who could qualify 
they must remain in the united states to remain eligible 
the statement said all salvadorans who are encountered by ins 
agents in enforcement actions while this program is in effect will 
be advised of the benefit and given the opportunity to show their 
eligibility 
