<TEXT>
international travelers arriving at kennedy 
airport may think the us customs inspectors checking their 
luggage look a tad babyfaced and theyre right some are as 
young as 14 
the youths are part of the boy scouts of americas explorer 
program but this group is not just interested in earning merit 
badges theyre looking for drugs weapons and counterfeit goods 
these explorers are involved in nearly every aspect of customs 
activities from searching foreign cargo planes to xraying cartons 
of frozen shrimp 
before going out in the field they attend classes where they 
learn essentials like search arrest and seizure techniques and how 
to conduct a proper patdown later theyll also perform 
surveillance with agents investigating money laundering and child 
pornography 
sunds exciting right most days it is the group insists they 
get to meet a lot of celebrities steve martin and mel brooks among 
them but they also discover theres a downside as well 
like rummaging through someones sweaty dirty underwear or 
sniffing the contents of a suspicious vial only to learn a dozen 
sneezes too late that its chili powder or being pelted with 
overripe illegal fruit by passengers who believe if i cant 
have it neither can you 
yeah i came in here really thinking that every day was going 
to be like miami vice said donald pearce 20 of queens 
trust me its not 
the program which began in 1984 is designed to give handson 
experience and help participants decide if they want a career in 
law enforcement said customs officer patricia leyden post 
supervisor 
it also gives them a different view of what life is like 
she said some of them come from disadvantaged homes or 
neighborhoods where kids dont grow up with the greatest dreams in 
the world this program hopefully teaches them they can do 
something positive with their lives 
the latter is what attracted pearce he joined the group at 15 
and is in college pursuing a degree in criminal justice 
i grew up in a rapidly changing community the crime rate was 
going up drugs were everywhere i could have stayed out on the 
streets with my friends but i knew where they were headed 
pearce said 
i didnt want to be 21 with a ged and have a motorcycle be the 
most important thing in my life 
nationwide some 11 million youths are involved in explorer 
programs that run the gamut from movie producing to medicine and 
commercial art to aerospace engineering 
brian archimbaud director of exploring for the boy scout 
council in new york said the focus shifted from camping and nature 
programs around 1970 after a survey showed senior scouts wanted 
careeroriented programs 
they also not surprisingly wanted a program that had girls 
in it archimbaud said 
the 11 males and three females at the kennedy post who range in 
age from 14 to 20 nearly blend in with their official us customs 
counterparts helping enforce the laws of 40 federal agencies 
only their youthful faces and trendy hairdos give them away 
dressed in the customs uniform of starched white shirts and blue 
trousers they politely answer travelers questions as they look 
through luggage for contraband 
though the explorers havent been in on any big busts they have 
had some small successes 
charles sierra a serious bearded 19yearold who refused to 
smile for a photographer because he was on duty found a 
carton of guns in a shipment of luggage while working cargo 
inspection 
david chianes a 16yearold nicknamed bart because of his 
simpsonlike hairdo uncovered 40 ounces of opium inside some 
hollowed tree branches while working the mailroom detail they 
were just regular branches but they smelled funny the youthful 
sleuth said 
and then there was the great mango caper said robert nici 
19 giving a companion a high five 
nici tie slightly askew busily chomping gum recalls how he 
discovered an illegal cache of mangoes inside a caribbean womans 
suitcase he was the one who got pelted 
you think youve got the big load here the one thats going 
to make medellin cartel crumble and it turns out to be illegal 
fruit 
though he made light of his big bust leyden gently reminded him 
that he might have stopped another mediterranean fruit fly 
infestation a fact that prompted another high five 
of all the jobs the explorers seem to like doing plane searches 
best 
its the lttle kids in them leyden said they get to go 
in and search the electrical systems under floors looking for 
whatever 
most volunteer between 10 and 30 hours a month at the airport 
they also give antidrug lectures at high schools and community 
fairs 
to become an explorer no previous scouting experience is 
necessary members must be between 14 and 20 and if in high 
school maintain a c average the mix nationwide is 60 percent 
male and 40 percent female 
though the group falls under the auspices of the boy scouts the 
program is run through the participating agency or business 
archimbaud said about 60 percent of the explorers go into some 
aspect of their career posts two former members of the jfk post 
now are working as fulltime customs inspectors 
the rest go off in a totally different direction archimbaud 
said thats one of the programs main advantages they get to 
experience different careers before theyre forced to make a 
serious commitment 
he knows firsthand the benefits of the program his daughter was 
a journalism explorer at a dallas newspaper 
by her exposure to a newspaper she got a real good sense of 
what the career had to offer the pluses the drawbacks pause 
and as a result shes in law school today 
