<TEXT>
if ever a man has had his sense of humor put 
to the test its robert polhill 
first hes held hostage by lebanese extremists more than three 
years and being diabetic must find a way to get daily insulin 
from captors who dont speak his language 
then when the former beirut university college lecturer is 
released he learns he has throat cancer and must have his voice 
box removed 
now polhill at 56 is without a job breathing through a hole 
in his neck and trying to get people to understand him through a 
fatiguing process called esophageal speech 
still the oneliners keep coming 
ill talk again he wrote on a yellow pad but im a 
realist too ill never have another hit record 
polhill was taken hostage jan 24 1987 and freed last april 
22 three and a half weeks later doctors at walter reed hospital 
removed his larynx a short time later he and his wife moved into 
a hospital apartment near the speech clinic where he gets therapy 
twice a day 
hes an aplus student said prof william t simpkins jr 
he made a sound the first month after surgery at four months 
hes where many people are at six months 
polhill said that for 39 years including his days as a hostage 
he smoked up to four packs of cigarettes a day more than 90 
percent of the 25000 people who require the surgery were heavy 
smokers simpkins said 
he was always smoking said polhills wife ferial he got 
up in the middle of the night to smoke 
polhill cant smoke anymore because he no longer can breathe 
through his nose and mouth 
he talks by capturing air between his tongue and teeth and 
compressing it to create sounds that and notewriting are the 
ways he answers questions 
laryngectomy patients who perfect this esophageal speech sound 
like normal talkers with headcolds simpkins said 
polhill said he rejected the electronic device preferred by some 
throatcancer victims because you sound like you are trying out 
for star wars 
tall and slim polhill is generally lowkey bantering playfully 
with his wife and cracking jokes with visitors when he tires of 
talking he reaches for his pencil and pad and keeps the 
conversation going in neat precise print 
he bristled only once when he was asked if losing his voice was 
worse than being a hostage 
to me there is no comparison to being chained to the floor 
he said you couldnt even get up to go to the bathroom 
when polhill was released he was quoted as saying he strived 
to continue to be angry as a means of coping with captivity 
later he said he was angry at being a captive but not consumed 
by it 
the point was that anger is a great energizer he said 
then you use humor to tone it down and rechannel it more 
productively 
i guess ive always been able to laugh at myself said 
polhill i didnt have the psychological problems i was expected 
to have 
he said a state department psychiatrist was assigned to him at 
damascus immediately after he was released but by the time they 
reached wiesbaden germany the two men were friends not doctor 
and patient 
they warned me that he would go into a depression ferial 
polhill said but i said i dont think so 
polhills plans for the future are vague a certified public 
accountant he said hes too out of date to step right back into an 
accounting job 
all of my energy to date has been devoted to the return to 
freedom recovery from cancer and learning to talk he said 
his medical bills and living arrangements have been handled by 
the government since his release though he knows uncle sams 
generosity wont go on forever 
id like to write id like to speak and teach again he 
said he also said he would like to help diabetics throat cancer 
patients and hostages and their families 
ferial polhill who is palestinian and fluent in arabic english 
and french is ready to go back to work she and robert met in 
cyprus when she was an office manager at the international 
accounting firm for which he worked an openly affectionate couple 
theyve been married for 10 years 
they will move wherever there is a job opportunity polhill 
said but he would like to stay in the united states 
meanwhile the couples social life has included functions 
arranged by no greater love a nonprofit organizations that helps 
hostages and their families and the american diabetes association 
which published polhills account of how he coped with his diabetes 
as a captive 
in the associations forecast magazine he wrote about how he 
and another diabetic hostage took care of each other and 
communicated their needs to their captors otherwise he declines 
to give extensive details about his 1182 days as a captive 
i have a responsibility to those still there he said 
ive made my recommendations directly to the man who can do 
something i have no public recommendations to make 
he said president bush listened intently and took notes when 
they met shortly after polhill was released 
ferial polhill said if her husband wants to discuss his days as 
a hostage shes there to listen but she doesnt ask questions and 
doesnt feel a need to know the details 
thinking about it doesnt bother me said polhill but 
does the world need to know 
while polhill was a captive ferial stayed on in beirut the 
city where she grew up trying to find her husband she left only 
when fighting became intolerable but returned later and was in 
beirut when robert was released 
she said people have been surprised at how easily the couple has 
adjusted to being together again after the long ordeal 
its as if we were stepping back in time she said we 
fell back into our lives as if nothing had happened 
she said her friends have asked her how her husband hollers at 
her now that he has no voice box 
i say his writing gets very messy she said 
thats whats depressing joked polhill i cant shout at 
her anymore 
</TEXT>
