<TEXT>
the bankruptcy court filing by continental 
airlines leaves an empire built by ousted chairman frank lorenzo in 
disarray but the carrier says it will continue flying while it 
tries to reorganize 
the nations fifthlargest airline blamed 22 billion in debt 
and increased jet fuel costs due to the persian gulf crisis for 
mondays decision to seek protection from creditors under chapter 
11 of federal bankruptcy laws 
continental said the move did not affect any of about 1400 
flights monday the airline serves 88 us cities and 55 
international destinations with more than 300 planes its main hubs 
are in newark nj houston and denver and the airline is 
building up a fourth hub in cleveland 
management sought to reassure the airlines passengers and 
37000 employees the carrier planned to emerge from bankruptcy 
court as an operating entity the airline would fly its normal 
schedule and honor contracts with travel agents and other airlines 
we are confident that there will be no need for layoffs pay 
cuts or reductions in benefits said hollis harris chairman of 
continental airlines holdings inc the airlines parent which 
also filed for chapter 11 
the move though leaves in tatters an empire crafted by lorenzo 
from a hodgepodge of carriers including eastern airlines people 
express and frontier and its huge debt is a legacy of its growth 
during the 1980s 
subsidiary eastern is struggling as it seeks to reorganize after 
filing for bankruptcy protection in 1989 lorenzo was ousted as 
chairman earlier this year and his texas air corp was renamed 
the trip to bankruptcy court was the second in seven years by 
continental which filed in 1983 amid a bitter labor dispute with 
the airlines union under chapter 11 a company gets a reprieve 
from debts while it figures out how to pay bills and tries to 
reorganize as a healthy business 
this is not a bankruptcy as was continentals in 1983 or 
easterns last year continentals general counsel charles t 
goolsbee said remember those airlines shut down we are 
doing none of that this is absolutely a businessasusual 
program 
some analysts said continental may have a relatively smooth ride 
through bankruptcy court but recent shakeouts in the industry and 
the uncertainty of the middle east situation remain troubling 
its still a strong airline said raymond neidl an analyst 
with dillon read amp co a wall street investment firm theyve 
got good hubs and fairly cheap operating costs they want to hold 
onto most of these assets in the long term that could be good 
continental said it had agreed to sell its seattletacoma to 
tokyo route to american airlines for 150 million pending 
bankruptcy court approval the route sale is to be concluded at the 
end of 1991 but 140 million of the sale price is expected to be 
advanced to continental before the deal closes 
as part of the sale continental withdrew its other 
international routes from the market last month continental put 
those up for sale instead of seeking bankruptcy protection 
continental has about 22 billion in outstanding debt about 
17 billion of which is secured it also has nearly 4 billion in 
aircraft operating losses 
harris said the airline is spending an extra 70 million a month 
on jet fuel because of a sharp rise since iraq invaded kuwait in 
august prices more than doubled from about 57 cents in july to 
128 in midoctober before falling back in recent weeks 
continental now is paying 107 per gallon in addition the 
airline has increased passenger fares 15 percent in recent months 
but spokesman ned walker said the hikes come nowhere near to 
recovering our fuel costs 
continental lost 883 million in the third quarter of this 
year compared to a loss of 158 million in 1989 for the first 
nine months losses totaled 97 million compared with 523 million 
in the same period a year ago 
rising jet fuel costs have affected other airlines but none had 
filed for chapter 11 before continental 
earlier this fall pan am corp announced it would sell five 
prized london routes to ual corp the parent of united in a 400 
million deal in addition airlines have laid of thousands of 
workers and some plan to cut capacities 
