<DOCNO> AP901204-0196 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the success of continental airlines decision to 
file for bankruptcy court protection might depend on how long tough 
times linger in an industry ravaged by high fuel costs and a 
sinking economy analysts say 
passengers should see no changes in continentals service as the 
houstonbased carrier buys time and holds creditors at bay for 
now anyway but analysts said the strategy depends on outside 
factors changing 
theyre trying to hold the thing together as much as possible 
and try to wait it out said thomas canning at standard amp poors 
corp a leading debtrating agency it could work provided this 
recession is not too prolonged and too deep 
if on the other hand continental and other weak airlines 
continue bleeding and even go out of business financially powerful 
airlines such as american and united will be in a much better 
position that could mean for example fewer fare discounts and 
even some big fare increases as competition declines 
even as continental announced the chapter 11 filing monday it 
said it was selling a prized seattletokyo route to american for 
150 million the move seemed to affirm the view of analysts who 
have said the persian gulf crisis is serving as a catalyst to speed 
industry shakeups 
the bankruptcy filing appeared to have been necessary because 
of a liquidity crisis where assets could not be sold in a good time 
frame said raymond neidl an analyst with dillon read amp co 
the other major airline in bankruptcy court is eastern a 
continental subsidiary it ran into lifethreatening troubles this 
fall when unsecured creditors asked a bankruptcy judge to order a 
liquidation saying eastern has no chance of a healthy recovery 
but last week easterns courtappointed trustee martin r 
shugrue jr persuaded a bankruptcy judge to give eastern up to 135 
million from an escrow fund shugrue said the cash will keep 
eastern alive through march and after that he believes the airline 
can stop losing money 
analysts dont believe it will be that simple but they say 
easterns experience shows that an airline can stay alive in 
bankruptcy court indefinitely 
as weve seen them with the eastern bankruptcy the airline 
under the protection of chapter 11 can continue as a very 
effective competitor said bruce thorp airline analyst with 
provident national bank in philadelphia 
in fact easterns presence is very much felt by competitors 
such as delta he said the important point here is going into 
chapter 11 does not take you out of business by any means 
