<TEXT>
gordon becker never stops thinking about 
christmas 
as president and founder of becker group the nations largest 
retail decorator visions of sugar plums dance round his head all 
year as he concocts ways to turn ubiquitous shopping centers and 
malls into customerluring winter wonderlands 
the companys creations go beyond strings of lights and plywood 
reindeer there are castles and christmas trees as tall as office 
buildings there are scenes of disney characters sesame street 
creatures peanuts rudolph the rednose reindeer and garfield the 
cat 
becker group installed new displays in 145 shopping centers and 
malls this year at an average cost of 100000 apiece the 
companys clientele though totals 350 malls and centers 
nationwide 
becker said revenue for the privatly owned company is expected 
to exceed 13 million in 1990 with the christmas decorations 
accounting for nearly 95 percent of business 
its a fun business but there are nervewracking moments 
said the slightly rotund 57yearold becker a former store santa 
beckers busiest time is the two months before christmas when 
the company ships and assembles its christmas creations throughout 
the year hes taking orders making plans and surveying malls and 
stores 
business wasnt always so brisk however 
becker said he was forced to file for bankruptcy protection 
under chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws in 1976 although 
he managed to stay in business he struggled until 1983 when 
things finally started to take off 
it was that year when becker began targeting developers who own 
groups of malls those contracts now comprise 60 percent of his 
business 
i was meeting with a developer in dallas in 1983 and he told 
me i might have a good year he had 12 malls and he was thinking 
about giving me five or six becker said i said why not all 
12 i came back with almost a million dollar order 
revenue immediately jumped from 3 million where it had been 
mired for several years to 47 million 
today beckers company decorates malls for 13 developers 
including taubman co which owns 22 shopping centers and the 
edward j debartolo corp which owns 17 shopping centers the san 
francisco 49ers and the pittsburgh penguins hockey team 
among his clients the northwest plaza in st louis mo 
recently paid becker 400000 for a giant santa castle complete 
with 50foot banners strung through 10foot high wreaths the owner 
of the mall is the new yorkbased development company paramount 
group inc which owns three other malls in the united states all 
are clients of becker 
we probably do the largest santa photo concession because its 
so breathtaking people will drive from miles around to get their 
picture taken in our santa castle rather than somewhere else 
said christi parks marketing director for northwest plaza 
theres absolutely no doubt its worth the money we spent on 
it she said our mall has always had a reputation for having 
special christmas decorations for us to do something every few 
feet was not acceptable we literally need to fill the mall with 
christmas 
fair lane and twelve oaks shopping centers in detroit spent more 
than 350000 each on becker holiday decorations at cherry creek 
mall in denver becker provided a 52foot high christmas tree that 
measures 28 feet in diameter 
the cranberry mall in westminster md paid 50000 for its 
help garfield find pooky display several garfield figures 
powered by compressed air pop up in a house as the fat orange 
cartoon cat searches for his favorite stuffed animal 
most of becker groups decorations fall in the traditional line 
and the more elaborate fifth avenue line becker said 
displays last about three years meaning one third of the 
companys customers purchase new decorations every year 
beckers passion for christmas began in high school when he 
worked as a store santa for some pocket money for the holidays 
after he graduated from the university of maryland he started a 
santa school and rental business 
the school was abandoned in the early 1960s as he became more 
involved in the decorating business 
when it started 35 years ago my office was my bedroom in my 
mothers house and the garage was a warehouse said becker who 
operates today out of a 19th century townhouse in a fashionable 
neighborhood in baltimore the firm employs more thn 100 people 
in the 1950s you have to remember shopping centers were new 
there were no companies that existed you had to really juryrig 
everything recalled becker 
in the beginning he said he would do anything for a client and 
became known for setting up spotlights in front of stores 
becker said a background in show business helped his father 
lou becker was a bandleader who worked with tommy and jimmy 
dorsey 
its theater in its purest form he said the way we deal 
with people there are the same technical problems as in mounting a 
show 
it has to look like the empire state building but when its 
over two guys have to be able to pack it up and put it away 
