british airways said tuesday it is seeking to 
create a new berlinbased airline which would compete with the 
german carrier lufthansa 
such an airline which aims to turn berlin into a hub could 
expand greatly in coming years by providing eastwest european air 
services and feeding into longhaul transcontinental flights 
british airways would hold a 49 percent stake in the new 
carrier and unspecified german investors would own the rest said 
a british airways spokeswoman who wasnt identified in accordance 
with airline practice 
we are still talking to a number of german interests its not 
going to be an immediate announcement its very much at the 
planning stages she said 
the new airline as yet unnamed isnt expected to begin 
operating until 1993 
british airways is advertising in the trade press for pilots in 
preparation for the airlines creation the spokeswoman said 
the carrier has been spurred to seek such a deal by german 
unification which effectively forces foreign carriers out of 
germany by 1993 
british airways currently operates a berlinbased fleet of nine 
airplanes providing 86 daily flights to nine german cities 
were keen to continue to operate in berlin weve been in 
there for 44 years we want to continue and expand it the 
spokeswoman said 
british airways has served berlin since world war ii when it 
flew in supplies as part of the airlifts through which the allied 
forces replenished the blockaded city 
after the berlin wall came down pan american world airways the 
primary provider of berlin air services sold its operations to 
lufthansa which had been prohibited from operating out of berlins 
tegl airport since the war 
british airways which has transformed itself from a poor 
