<TEXT>
talks to revamp the world free trading 
system are very close to collapse a us trade official said 
today 
ambassador rufus yerxa a deputy us trade representative told 
a news conference the european community had not responded to 
demands from most other countries for greater liberalization on 
farm trade 
its quite clear the ball is now in the communitys court 
he said 
yerxa asked about australian trade minister neal blewetts 
statement that something had to give by the days end replied 
it is safe to say we share the concern of minister blewett of 
australia that these negotiations are very close to collapse 
president bush in uruguay the birthplace of the socalled 
uruguay round talks expressed hope that the negotiations might yet 
succeed 
we must use this meeting to find the political will to limit 
or reduce distortions in trade bush said 
yerxa said it was highly unlikely there would be further 
negotiations unless the ec changed its position no talks on the 
key farm trade question were scheduled 
as he spoke ec trade ministers were gathering to discuss their 
position in talks under the general agreement on tariffs and trade 
a treaty pledging its members to free trade 
despite pressure from many sides on the europeans for deep cuts 
in the ecs costly farm support programs community officials 
showed no willingness to make new reductions in their agriculture 
offer at the 107nation uruguay round the most ambitious trade 
talks ever 
there is absolutely no hope of having an agreement this 
afternoon or even tomorrow afternoon but possibly by friday 
said ray macsharry the farm chief of the 12nation trading bloc 
officials are locked in a makeorbreak effort to overhaul the 
global trading system by weeks end 
the comprehensive agreement they are seeking would lower trade 
barriers and write new rules covering trade in 15 areas including 
agriculture manufactured goods textiles trademarks and patents 
and services such as banking and telecommunications 
the uruguay round bargaining which opened in 1986 in the 
uruguayan resort of punta del este has broken down in recent 
months because of a stubborn fight between the european community 
and its major trading partners over government payments to farmers 
the united states backed by argentina australia and other 
nations has demanded so far without results that the european 
community peel away much of the support program for its 10 million 
farmers 
there appeared to be growing anger over the communitys refusal 
to budge on agriculture which a number of nations including the 
united states australia and argentina have said is key to an 
overall deal 
the ec has offered to trim only 30 percent in subsidies for 
major crops over a 10year period counting from 1986 the united 
states is urging it to slash subsidies by 75 percent to 90 percent 
over the next decade 
canadian state minister charles mayer dismissed the communitys 
offer as mumbo jumbo and said in our country someone who 
comes around selling snake oil we call him a quack 
many european farmers view the subsidy cuts as threatening their 
livelihood police fired tear gas and water cannons monday to 
disperse 30000 farmers outside the european parliament building in 
the belgian capital 
the united states believes that without a commitment to reduce 
farm subsidies third world countries will walk away from the 
negotiations dooming any chances to get new trade rules to cover 
service industries and copyright theft 
third world leaders say the subsidies steal potential markets 
from their farmers ruining agriculture in their countries 
