<DOCNO> AP901204-0238 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the conviction of robert morris for unleashing a 
computer worm program in 1988 should be overturned because he 
didnt intend to paralyze thousands of computers linked to a 
nationwide program his attorney told an appeals court tuesday 
the oral arguments in morris appeal were presented to three 
judges of the 2nd us circuit court of appeals who didnt 
immediately make a decision 
morris 25 of arnold md was the first person brought to 
trial under a section of a 1986 federal computer fraud and abuse 
law that makes it a felony to break into a federal computer network 
and prevent authorized use of the system 
the former cornell university student was convicted at trial and 
sentenced to three years probation 400 hours of community service 
and a 10000 fine 
the appeal presentations of defense attorney thomas guidoboni 
and the prosecutor justice department attorney ellen meltzer 
focused on their different interpretations of the law which a 
federal jury in syracuse found morris violated 
morris worm immobilized an estimated 6000 computers linked to 
the internet network including ones at nasa military facilities 
and major universities witnesses testified that it did not 
permanently harm the computers or computer files but in some cases 
victims were unable to use their computers for several days while 
the worm was hunted down and removed from their computers 
morris testified during his trial that he had made a programming 
error that caused the worm to go berserk and cripple the internet 
system on nov 2 1988 
he said he did not intend to cause permanent damage to computer 
files only to infiltrate the networks security 
in court tuesday guidoboni said he interpreted the computer 
fraud law to mean that the government had to prove that morris not 
only intended to access the computer program but also planned to 
interrupt access for others 
he said there was insufficient evidence to support his 
interpretation of the statute 
the lawyer also claimed morris did not break into computers 
illegally but rather merely exceeded authority already given to 
him for computer access 
meltzer however argued that the conviction should stand 
because the language of the law explicitly stated that proof that a 
hacker intended to cause damage or loss to others was not required 
the appeals court will issue a written opinion at a later date 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

