<TEXT>
sales of new homes dropped 35 percent in 
october to the lowest level in eight years the government reported 
tuesday but analysts said the free fall may be bottoming out and 
sales should begin rebounding by spring 
sales should be leveling off at this number in the fourth 
quarter and the first quarter of next year assuming mortgage 
rates continue to fall and the mideast problem is resolved said 
economist david g seiders of the national association of home 
builders 
economist mark obrinsky of the federal national mortgage 
association suggested sales may zigzag for several months but 
assuming no blowup in the middle east i expect to see a more 
sustained pickup by spring of 1991 
sales totaled a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 491000 the 
departments of commerce and housing and urban development said in a 
joint release that was the lowest since 480000 new homes were 
sold in october 1982 a month before the 198182 recession ended 
so far this year new home sales were off 158 percent from the 
same period of 1989 
sales fell 4 percent in september and 2 percent in august the 
september figure was revised down from 6 percent in the 
departments initial estimate but the october total was worse than 
the 18 percent drop first reported 
obrinsky said the main reason for the decline is great 
consumer uncertainty and generally negative buying sentiment 
consumers he said are experiencing rising prices caused by the 
persian gulf crisis and increasing unemployment as the economy 
slows 
but really the big one is the great uncertainty over the 
mideast concern over war breaking out obrinsky added 
at the october sales pace it would take 84 months to exhaust 
the inventory of unsold homes up from 83 months in september 
there was a sevenmonth supply of unsold homes in october 1989 
but richard peach an economist with the mortgage bankers 
association said builders are cutting back on housing starts to 
counter the slow sales 
and once the market recovers youre going to find relatively 
few new homes he said that in turn will drive up prices which 
have been declining recently 
the median price of a new home in october was 121800 up from 
112900 in september but down from 123000 a year ago the median 
means half of the homes cost more half less 
seiders attributed the price increase to a hefty 474 percent 
gain in sales in the northeast which has the highest housing costs 
in the nation sales there totaled an annual rate of 84000 units 
after falling 129 percent the previous month 
sales in all other regions fell including a drop of 182 
percent in the west to 112000 units that was the lowest since 
106000 homes were sold in september 1982 
in the midwest sales were off 117 percent to 83000 units 
the lowest since 74000 homes were sold in august 1986 sales 
dropped 41 percent in the south to 212000 units 
