a defense attorney conceded tuesday that a 
soybean trader at the chicago board of trade broke exchange rules 
but said he did not attempt to cheat customers or commit fraud 
the comments came during closing argumnents in the 11weekold 
trial of 10 soybean traders and brokers charged in a federal 
investigation of alleged corruption at the board of trade and 
chicago mercantile exchange 
attorney jim epstein called the governments evidence 
insubstantial conceded violations of board of trade rules and 
vigorously denied charges of wire fraud mail fraud and 
racketeering conspiracy 
did he violate the rules absolutely epstein said of his 
client martin j dempsey did he attempt to commit fraud 
absolutely not 
epstein told a federal court jury that testimony indicated many 
of the rule violations were common on the trading floor and often 
benefited customers for whom the defendants may have been trading 
one such violation is curb trading which occurs in the trading 
pit in the seconds or minutes after the closing bell 
sure he did curb trading epstein said of dempsey is he 
proud of it no did he try to conceal it of course he did but 
not because he was committing fraud but because he was 
breaking the rules 
the defense contended the prosecution wanted the jury believe 
concealing the trades was a sign of trying to cheat customers 
other than breaking the rule youre not cheating anyone 
epstein said 
the attorney also contended that government witnesses lied and 
presented misleading testimony 
